There's a major bug where I'm unable to destroy the two user accounts I created without a rails exception (masked by Heroku's "something went wrong").

There's a minor bug where I'm unable to purchase a ticket for a flight that leaves tomorrow (3-1-21) at 19:50 UTC. The current datetime is 2021 - 03 - 01 x 03:54:17 UTC so I should be able to reserve this flight. It looks like you've got the year-2000 time 'bug' from storing date/time separately, you might look into updating your time type into a datetime, which simplifies the calculation of whether a flight has or has not happened yet for all your comparisons. Also it would be nice if arrival times could be set for flights as employees enter the data into the system.

comment:
All attributes are present. but I would consider adding the credit cards as part of the User form.

This is because, while trying to book a flight as an admin, the credit card dropdown doesn't list any cards, unless I go and add a card first. Another reason to look into this, is because, it is an attribute of the user. So if I add a card individually, I have no link with the created card and the user/admin creating it. For instance, I created two cards for testing admin but I have no way of accessing that at the user end as they have no connection with the user I created while being an admin. (I hope it's clear)

So if you want to retain this functionality, a better way to do so would be to include 'add a card' link to the flight booking page itself(in place of a drop down). Further a more meaningful way, is to make avilable the admin cards(which were already there in the card list when i started testing) to be available for the dropdown in the flight booking page. 

If your thinking was to not enable non-admin cards to the admin for purchasing a flight, again you could add the card information to the user's form(pre-recorded in case of admin) and then display it in the dropdown for booking a flight.

Credit - card functionality -- 

  • The system is accepting expired cards as well. You may want to include a filter for that.
  • Another thing I noticed many people applying to theirs is the check that a credit card contains 16 numbers. You may want to implement that as well, if you see fit.

If you're still working on how to do this (easily) I highly recommend looking into sending emails via a gmail account instead of going to the hassle of setting up a smtp server on your production device. The attributes are all in place for flights as specified! The following are some points I found out hwile testing. It may help you while going over the app:- 

  • When logged in as a user, I'm able to edit flight details. I think you should restrict this to just the admin. Consider maybe adding check "if current_user == admin?" to the Edit button on the Show paage for a given flight. 
  • Also you may want to switch the redirection of Back in the Show page of a given flight to the view containing all flights.
  • In all flights, on 2021-03-27, there are three possible flights available, but in flights/lookup page, only one pair of destination-origin airports are visible in dropdown. Maybe this could be looked at?

Are there any methods that are doing more than 1 task? One method should only handle one task, if there are multiple tasks, there should be function calls. Mention examples of where this is not the case.
comment:
application_controller.rb - In this file, I see there are two methods def find_roundtrip(flight) and def find_replacement(flight). These methods could probably be moved, most likely to the to the flight controller.

feedbacks_controller.rb - In this file, in the new method, there is some extraneous logic that would probably be better suited to be moved into its own method, reducing the clutter of new.

 For the most part, the methods were constrained to singular tasks and methods were organized nicely. There are perhaps a few things that could be changed, as noted above (although the two listed above are not exhaustive, probably).

comment: In several cases, controller methods that aren't part of the users/session system (eg CreditCardsController, ReservationsController) are handling session-checks using if current_user.id != nil as well as setting up the models to be worked on and passing these data to the views. This could be made more DRY by implementing a helper method at the ApplicationController level that checks whether a session is valid (logged in), which is then called by a before_action in the various controllers. Also, within the destroy methods of several controllers, the logic to destroy associated objects is being handled manually before destroying (this) object. This could be handled in a more rails-istic fasion by setting the destroy: dependents association in the model of each object which would eliminate the object.each do |block| to destroy associations (flights controller#destroy, users controller#destroy)

comment:
In a lot of the controller functions. methods are not being used for tasks inside the CRUD actions.

For example in reservations controller, create is doing many things inside of it that should be moved to a private method instead for the create action.

This same sort of thing happens in update as well. 

For example below, this functionality can be moved inside a method in the private section of the class and a method can be called to accomplish this inside update.

if reservation_params[:fp].to_i == 1
  flight = Flight.find_by(flight_number: reservation_params[:Replacement])
  reservationParams[:flight_id] = flight.id
end

reservationParams.delete :fp
reservationParams.delete :flight_number
reservationParams.delete :Replacement

def set_feedback
  @feedback = Feedback.find(params[:id])

# Only allow a list of trusted parameters through.
def feedback_params
  params.require(:feedback).permit(:feedback_response, :flight_number)
end

txt: Are there methods that have convoluted logic/many nested loops? Mention examples of where this is the case.
comment:
Inside of the create action of the reservation controller, there is an instance where there are nested if loops that are somewhat convoluted.

There are two nested if conditions on top of an if condition. This can be moved into private methods that can call on each other.

Below is the example I am speaking of.

  if @reservation.save
    ReservationMailer.with(reservation: @reservation, user: current_user).reservation_email.deliver_now

    if flight_preference.to_i == 1

      from = Flight.find_by(flight_number: roundtrip)

      #flight capacity check.
      reservations = Reservation.where(flight: from)
      if reservations.length >= from.flight_capacity
        respond_to do |format|
          @reservation.errors.add(:base, "Flight capacity full when generating the returning flight")
          format.html { redirect_to reservations_path, status: :unprocessable_entity }
          format.json { render json: @reservation.errors, status: :unprocessable_entity }
        end
      end

      @reservation_from = Reservation.new(reservationParam)

      @reservation_from.user = current_user
      @reservation_from.flight = from
      @reservation_from.confirmation_number = Reservation.last.nil? ? 1 : Reservation.last.id + 1

      #save the second reservation
      if @reservation_from.save
        ReservationMailer.with(reservation: @reservation_from, user: current_user).reservation_email.deliver_now
        format.html { redirect_to reservations_path, notice: "Reservation was successfully created." }
        format.json { render :show, status: :created, location: @reservation_from }
      else
        format.html { render :new, status: :unprocessable_entity }
        format.json { render json: @reservation.errors, status: :unprocessable_entity }
      end
    else
      format.html { redirect_to reservations_path, notice: "Reservation was successfully created." }
      format.json { render :show, status: :created, location: @reservation }
    end
  else
    format.html { render :new, status: :unprocessable_entity }
    format.json { render json: @reservation.errors, status: :unprocessable_entity }
  end
end
name: Tuffy

txt: How well does the code follow "good" Ruby on Rails coding practices?
comment:
The indentation and style of Ruby is followed closely in this code. There are no return statements being used which is Ruby like.

For example, these two private methods have no return statements in them but return the last statement in the method.

# Use callbacks to share common setup or constraints between actions.
def set_reservation
  @reservation = Reservation.find(params[:id])
end

# Only allow a list of trusted parameters through.
def reservation_params
  params.require(:reservation).permit(:user, :flight,
                                      :confirmation_number,
                                      :class_type, :flight_number,
                                      :flight_id,:round_trip_flight,
                                      :fp,:Replacement)
end

comment:
The authors have FIXED many of the previous issues including sending of emails, validations, flight search, change-of-flight-date, and feedbacks.

 

Still remaining ISSUES include:

  • Round trips are only partially implemented. In a real airline reservation system, round trips consist of two one-way trips with distinct departure/arrival dates that are related by sharing origin/destination pairs -- this way, users can pick different return dates. In this system, various flights are classed as "round trips" but only have a single departure date. Therefore, change-of-date also doesn't work quite right, but getting round trips to 100% implementation is not a far reach with your working flight query and date-change systems in place.
  • Change-of-date on a reservation allows me to select a date from the past (2017)
  • I am able to leave feedback multiple times for the same reservation.
name: HimesMakthalHanna

The system is very close to complete. Since the last round, the authors have FIXED and or improved: Email Sending, change-of-dates, round-trips.

 

These items are still not finished or working quite correctly:

  • Round trips, once booked, are still treated as a combination of one-way trips with no clear association between the trips. Also, it is possible to keep clicking "Book a round trip" over and over to build a 3-leg or 5-leg round trip, which would not be considered a normal round trip. This item is very close to completion.
  • Passenger lists are missing from the flights index and or show action as admin.

comment:
Logged in as a user, I do not get emails when I create a reservation.

Logged in as a user, I am able to select a Round Trip flight, but when I am taken back to the flights page to book the second leg there are no flights available. I assume there has to be a flight with the origin/destination switched available in the system, but I am not notified in any way when this condition is not met.

Logged in as a user, I am able to add new flights to the system.

I see that price is an attribute of the Flight model, but it is not displayed anywhere in the app.

Logged in as a user, I am able to book a reservation on a flight that has already passed. This is handy for testing feedback, but I don't think it is supposed to be possible.
